<br>
They basically had 3 stories.<br>
<br>
1) First was a guy who had a good job, a family, house, wife, 2 kids, etc.  But when he got home from work he 2-boxed all evening.  They showed time lapse of his gameplaying, and you could see the kids running up to say hi to their dad, running off, dinner being served, TV going on and off, etc.  All the while he's just sittin there dual-boxing.<br>
<br>
I thought that one was the truest and best commentary on the problems EQ can have.  Normallish people just spending way too much time on it, to the point of neglecting other social contact.<br>
<br>
2) 2nd story was Ben Steins kid, who basically played too much EQ, got sent to boarding school, and now doesn't play as much.  Ben Stein's initial descriptions sounded fairly accurate (that he was moody, that he was staying up all night playing, playing on the weekends, etc).  His later descriptions (that it was like he was possessed by a demon) were stupid.  <br>
<br>
3) 3rd story was that kid who killed himself.  My wife and I both agreed that EQ probably played a part in his death, but not necessarily because of the game was designed.  Two most probable causes we thought he killed himself for:<br>
   a) Had, or thought he had, a romance w/ someone in game, went bad, shot himself over it.<br>
   b) Got extremely depressed over the fact that he had thrown away everything he'd worked so hard for in order to play EQ (He quit his job, etc).<br>
<br>
They didn't show any &quot;well adjusted&quot; people who play EQ just a few hours a week, but they don't do that any time they talk about addiction (ie: when talking about gambling addiction, they don't do a story about someone who goes to Vegas once a year with a 200 dollar limit).<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uveldalina.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Veldalina</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/19/02 4:16:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1588.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_star.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Accountability</span><hr size=1> I've had a history with depression and I know (because I am this way) that people who are depressed will find some kind of &quot;escape&quot; from their lives.  It can be books, games, exercise, food, TV, chatrooms, anything that keeps their minds off of their real lives.  These people aren't happy with their lives, and in some ways the escapist behavior actually extends their lives, because at least then they have something in their life that doesn't feel like it hurts so much as real life.<br>
<br>
EQ makes an excellent escape.  You can choose what your avatar looks like, and this person is almost always an attractive, powerful member of their race.  This person is either a powerful soloer, fighting tough monsters all by themselves, or a class that's &quot;needed&quot; by others in groups - and there's nothing a depressed person who is unhappy and disconnected from their real life likes more than to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> needed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and appreciated by others.<br>
<br>
In EQ, you have so much control over what you do and don't do.  Your character is a free wanderer that makes coin and gains power through adventure, not someone who goes to a 9-5 job every day that probably won't ever go anywhere.  If someone starts getting angry at you, you can just /ignore them.  You can present what you want of yourself to other people; they don't have to know that you're a high school dropout in a deadend job, and they probably don't really care to know, either.  If you do your job well in a group, people will tell you so and you can bask in their praise, feeling like you're actually worthwhile.<br>
<br>
Personally I don't think that taking EQ away from a depressed person is going to help them.  It's not going to force them to &quot;be normal&quot; and make friends outside the computer environment.  They're just going to find some other escape.  EQ addiction is not the problem for these people.  It's just a symptom.<br>
<br>
I wish I could say what the solution was to help the underlying problems that these people face.  For some people, medication and psychiatric appointments may help their depression.  It's a good idea for their family to also visit their psychiatrist, to help the family help the depressed person, as well as to help the family cope with having a depressed family member.<br>
<br>
There's no easy solution.  You can't just prescribe a pill to make the person all better.  You also can't make them get better by &quot;forcing&quot; them out of the house to do things other than their chosen escape activity.  But blaming the symptoms for the root of the problem is as counterproductive as if doctors decided that the flu was caused by a stuffy nose. <p><div align="center"><center><img src="http://www.members.shaw.ca/vae/velsig.jpg"><BR>
<a href="http://www.byteoart.com/ledenyetz/"> Ledenyetz Troupe </a></div></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uirexes.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Irexes</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Bald Rogue</span><br>  Posts: 187<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/19/02 5:11:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1588.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_star.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Accountability</span><hr size=1> /applaud Velda <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uelhanamistfall.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ElhanaMistfall</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.mistfits.com/tgrobb/elhanaportsmall.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 16<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/19/02 6:39:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1588.topic&index=31>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_star.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Accountability</span><hr size=1> I agree, very well said.  People who are depressed need to find an outlet, and how they deal with things through that outlet is what people see, I suppose.  I've had some bad problems with depression myself (which I don't want to get into here), and I know at times EQ has been my outlet, and at other times, it's been reading... and other times, it has been other outlets.  I would say I was a lot more depressed before I got Everquest... now it's helped moderate that a bit, because I'm having more fun... and I also have a much healthier way of getting out some of my frustration and anxiety than taking it all out on myself (just like some other people play sports, exercise, take a walk, or read).. <p><center>
