<br>
When we make bad choices, some of us, or those close to us, sometimes try to place the blame as far away as possible.<br>
<br>
That song made my son kill himself.<br>
<br>
That game made my son kill himself.<br>
<br>
That (insert anything here) made my son (insert any bad behavior here).<br>
<br>
I have had personal experience with real addiction.  And I was to blame.  Thats right, me.  Not the drug, not my mom, not TV, not popular music, I was at fault.<br>
<br>
It is true that only certain things are actually physically addictive.  But almost anything can be psychologically addictive.  I've known potheads who were every bit as bad as heroin junkies when they didn't have weed.  I've seen people who honestly would not leave there house to go out because they had to watch TV.  I've seen people completely blow off all there real world friends to sit in chat rooms.<br>
<br>
Yes, EQ can be truely addictive.  But then again so can anything.  And if someone gets addicted to EQ and makes stupid decisions regarding their life because of it, it is not EQ's fault, anymore than it is TV's fault, or internet chat rooms fault.  It is the persons fault for not controling their own life.<br>
<br>
People blame the substance, and ignore the underlying problem.  Everyone needs an escape, but when the escape we choose takes over and becomes more important than the real world, we need to look at why we seek escape so much, not blame the escape we choose.<br>
<br>
/bleh.<br>
<br>
It's late, I need sleep, but I want to write about three more pages on this.  I'm going to leave it at that for now, and tomorrow when the chance comes, I'll expand and respond.<br>
<br>
Til then.<br>
